commit.message:
Implement simple query caching to avoid repeating questions

When writing rules, one may want to organize queries in a way that would
cause redundant queries being sent to the probed target. By adding this
caching mechanism, one can write rules without having to worry about
this.

This change depends on the "state" feature of Perl, available since
Perl 5.10.

Add signature for NSD 4.1.10 -- 4.3.1

Two signatures are introduced, the one that maches the initial query
masks a legacy signature for "3Com Office Connect Remote". To let fpdns
fall back to legacy signatures, we send a malformed notify packet and
verify that the way it is handled is consistent with how nsd handles it
before identifying it. If it doesn't match the expected behavior, we
can fall back to other rules or legacy signatures.

commit.message:
Identify Unbound 1.7.x to 1.9.x

All Unbound releases between 1.7.0 and 1.9.6 were tested and verified to
match these new rules. Prior to this change, none of them matched a
signature. The old rules matched up to 1.6.0, but for 1.6.1 to 1.6.8,
fpdns misidentifies Unbound as "Raiden DNSD" (and still does, even after
this change).

Existing unbound rules match up to 1.6.0

Versions between 1.6.1 and 1.6.8 are misidentified as Raiden DNSD.
Versions later than that are not recognized.

This was verified on versions 1.5.10 and 1.6.0; versions prior to 1.5.10
wasn't as easy to build due to openssl api changes.

Hack to work around an old problem in Net::DNS.  Up to Net::DNS 0.68
the notify opcode was coded as NS_NOTIFY_OP.  That was changed in version
0.69 through 0.71 with no backwards compatibility.  This hack
tests for the new NOTIFY and falls back to NS_NOTIFY_OP if necessary.

print [Old rules] or [New rules] in the fingerprint output so we
can get a handle on how well the new rules are working.

Net::DNS 0.68 was recently released and Net::DNS::Header no longer
has a data() method.  We were using the data() method to construct
a Packet.

Instead we now create the Packet first and then pass a reference
to Packet->header to fp2header() which sets all the header
parameters.

Now we test nameserver IPv6 addresses as well.  When fpdns is given
a hostname to probe, it will test both its IPv4 and IPv6 addresses
if the name has both A and AAAA records.  Also true for the -D option.

For most dual-stack name servers, this probably means we test it
twice.  However, sometimes the two addresses will be on different
servers or at least different processes, so the fingerprint might be
different.

make dnslookup() recognize IPv6 addresses passed to it.  The IPv6
regexp comes from http://download.dartware.com/thirdparty/test-ipv6-regex.pl
